anitabidari wrote:
> Iam using heretrix 1.10.2, and am seeing the below exception. Any idea
> why this is occuring? Appears to be a Heretrix bug. Is there a version
> of Heretrix available that has a fix for this?

There appear to be 3 separate exceptions below, and none are problems I 
recognize.

> 
> <Cleaner name="Cleaner-1"/> caught exception:
> java.util.NoSuchElementException
> java.util.NoSuchElementException
> at java.util.TreeMap.key(TreeMap.java:433)
> at java.util.TreeMap.firstKey(TreeMap.java:287)
> at
> com.sleepycat.je.cleaner.FileProcessor$LookAheadCache.nextOffset(FileProcessor.j\
> ava:1147)
> at
> com.sleepycat.je.cleaner.FileProcessor.processLN(FileProcessor.java:525)
> at
> com.sleepycat.je.cleaner.FileProcessor.processFile(FileProcessor.java:481)
> at
> com.sleepycat.je.cleaner.FileProcessor.doClean(FileProcessor.java:235)
> at
> com.sleepycat.je.cleaner.FileProcessor.onWakeup(FileProcessor.java:143)
> at
> com.sleepycat.je.utilint.DaemonThread.run(DaemonThread.java:189)
> at java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:595)
> Continuing

This is actually an exception in a background thread of the 
BerkeleyDB-JE library we use. I haven't seen this before. Have you seen 
it more than once?


> Exception in thread "waker for
> org.archive.crawler.admin.CrawlJob$MBeanCrawlController@19f03d7"
> java.util.NoSuchElementException
> at java.util.TreeMap.key(TreeMap.java:433)
> at java.util.TreeMap.firstKey(TreeMap.java:287)
> at java.util.TreeSet.first(TreeSet.java:407)
> at
> java.util.Collections$SynchronizedSortedSet.first(Collections.java:1749)
> at
> org.archive.crawler.frontier.WorkQueueFrontier.wakeQueues(WorkQueueFrontier.java\
> :788)
> at
> org.archive.crawler.frontier.WorkQueueFrontier$WakeTask.run(WorkQueueFrontier.ja\
> va:88)
> at java.util.TimerThread.mainLoop(Timer.java:512)
> at java.util.TimerThread.run(Timer.java:462)

This is an exception in a Heritrix frontier background thread for waking 
queues whose 'politeness slumber' has finished. It is also unfamiliar. 
It is curious that the exception comes from the same TreeMap method, 
though this structure is unrelated to the BDB-JE 'Cleaner' structures 
above.

> Exception in thread "ToeThread #79:
> http://tickets.aol.com/venue.adp?referrer=http%3a%2f%2ftickets%2eaol%2ecom%2f&vi\
> d=106714"
> java.lang.IncompatibleClassChangeError
> at
> java.util.ListResourceBundle.handleGetObject(ListResourceBundle.java:109)
> at java.util.ResourceBundle.getObject(ResourceBundle.java:319)
> at java.util.ResourceBundle.getString(ResourceBundle.java:285)
> at java.util.logging.Level.getLocalizedName(Level.java:224)
> at
> org.archive.util.OneLineSimpleLogger.format(OneLineSimpleLogger.java:85)
> at java.util.logging.StreamHandler.publish(StreamHandler.java:179)
> at
> java.util.logging.ConsoleHandler.publish(ConsoleHandler.java:88)
> at java.util.logging.Logger.log(Logger.java:428)
> at java.util.logging.Logger.doLog(Logger.java:450)
> at java.util.logging.Logger.log(Logger.java:539)
> at org.archive.crawler.framework.ToeThread.run(ToeThread.java:172)

This is really odd: an IncompatibleClassChangeError is pretty exotic and 
certainly shouldn't be triggered by as simple of a logging operation as
at org.archive.crawler.framework.ToeThread.run(ToeThread.java:172). 
(Beyond editting the system JARs on disk while Java was running, I'm not 
sure I'd know how to trigger this Exception on purpose.)

Taken together, these three unique and hard-to-explain exceptions make 
me suspect the hardware: RAM, CPU, or motherboard problems, such as from 
defects or overheating.

I would suggest testing the machine outside of Java -- such as an 
intense memtest or CPU stress test -- to see if anything shows as flaky.

- Gordon @ IA
